## Memory Leak Analysis & Fix: `ScrollTracker`

There are **three interlocking bugs** in this component. Each one is bad on its own; together they cause an exponential accumulation of event listeners that permanently pollutes `window`.

---

## Bug #1 — Missing Dependency Array (Effect Runs on Every Render)

```jsx
// ❌ No second argument — runs after EVERY render
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', ...);
    window.addEventListener('resize', ...);
});
```

Without a dependency array, React re-runs this effect after **every render**. The problem is that the scroll and resize handlers themselves call `setState`, which triggers a render, which re-runs the effect, which adds more listeners, which call `setState`...

**The compounding cycle:**
```
Mount → Effect runs → 2 listeners added
User scrolls → handler fires → setState × 3
Re-render → Effect runs AGAIN → 2 more listeners (now 4 total)
User scrolls → 4 handlers fire → setState × 12
Re-render → 2 more listeners added (now 6 total)
... and so on, accelerating with every scroll event
```

**Fix:** Pass an empty dependency array `[]` so the effect runs only once on mount.

---

## Bug #2 — No Cleanup Function (Listeners Never Removed)

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', ...);
    window.addEventListener('resize', ...);
    // ❌ No return () => { ... } — nothing is ever removed
});
```

When the user navigates away, React **unmounts** the component. Without a cleanup function, both listeners remain permanently attached to `window`. When the user navigates back, the component mounts again and adds **new** listeners on top of the ghost listeners from the previous mount. Each navigation cycle stacks more and more abandoned listeners.

**After 5 navigation cycles:** 10+ scroll handlers firing on every scroll event, all trying to call `setState` on components that no longer exist.

**Fix:** Return a cleanup function from `useEffect` that calls `removeEventListener`.

---

## Bug #3 — Anonymous Arrow Functions (Cleanup Is Impossible Even If You Tried)

```jsx
// ❌ A new anonymous function is created each time
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
    const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;
    ...
});

// This would silently fail — it's a DIFFERENT function instance:
window.removeEventListener('scroll', () => { ... }); // ❌ No-op
```

`removeEventListener` works by identity — it needs the **exact same function reference** that was passed to `addEventListener`. Every time you write `() => { ... }`, JavaScript creates a brand-new function object. That means even if you tried to write a cleanup, it would silently do nothing and the listeners would remain.

**Fix:** Define the handlers as named `const` variables inside the effect scope. Both `addEventListener` and `removeEventListener` then reference the same object.

---

## Bonus Bug #4 — Stale Closure on `lastScrollY`

```jsx
const [lastScrollY, setLastScrollY] = useState(0); // ← state

useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
        // ❌ This closes over the value of lastScrollY
        // at the time the effect ran, NOT the current value
        setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollY ? 'down' : 'up');
        setLastScrollY(currentScrollY); // This triggers a re-render...
        //                               ...but the handler still sees the old value
    });
}, [lastScrollY]); // Adding lastScrollY to deps "fixes" it but causes new listeners every scroll
```

`lastScrollY` is only used for comparison — it doesn't need to appear in the UI, so it doesn't need to be state at all. Using `useRef` gives you a mutable value that persists across renders, is always current inside closures, and **does not trigger re-renders when updated**.

---

## React 18 Strict Mode: A Development Amplifier

In development, React 18 Strict Mode **intentionally mounts → unmounts → remounts** every component to help surface exactly this type of bug. Without cleanup, you'd see the listener count double immediately on the first load — before the user has even scrolled. This makes the bug visible right away in dev tools rather than only after several navigation cycles in production.

```
Strict Mode lifecycle (development only):
  Mount  → Effect fires → 2 listeners added
  Unmount → No cleanup → 2 listeners remain as ghosts on window  ← BUG VISIBLE HERE
  Remount → Effect fires → 2 more listeners (now 4 on first load)
```

---

## Corrected Component

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

function ScrollTracker() {
    const [scrollY, setScrollY] = useState(0);
    const [scrollDirection, setScrollDirection] = useState('none');

    // ✅ useRef instead of useState: no re-render on update,
    //    always holds the current value inside closures
    const lastScrollYRef = useRef(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        // ✅ Named functions — both addEventListener and removeEventListener
        //    reference the exact same function objects
        const handleScroll = () => {
            const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;

            // ✅ Reading from ref gives the current value, not a stale closure value
            setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollYRef.current ? 'down' : 'up');

            // ✅ Mutating the ref does not trigger a re-render
            lastScrollYRef.current = currentScrollY;

            setScrollY(currentScrollY);
        };

        const handleResize = () => {
            console.log('Window resized, recalculating...');
            setScrollY(window.scrollY);
        };

        window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
        window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

        // ✅ Cleanup: runs when the component unmounts (or before the effect re-runs)
        //    Removes the exact same function references that were added above
        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
            window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
        };
    }, []); // ✅ Empty array: effect runs only once (on mount), cleanup runs on unmount

    return (
        <div style={{ position: 'fixed', top: 10, right: 10, padding: '10px', background: '#333', color: '#fff' }}>
            <p>Scroll Y: {scrollY}</p>
            <p>Direction: {scrollDirection}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default ScrollTracker;
```

---

## Summary Table

| Problem | Root Cause | Effect |
|---|---|---|
| No dependency array `[]` | Effect re-runs on every render | New listeners added after every state change |
| No cleanup `return () => {}` | Listeners never removed | Ghost listeners persist across unmounts |
| Anonymous arrow functions | New function instance each call | `removeEventListener` silently fails even if called |
| `lastScrollY` as state | Re-render on update + stale closures | Direction detection is wrong; causes extra renders |

The corrected component uses exactly **two** `window` listeners for the entire lifetime of the component, removes both cleanly on unmount, and reads `lastScrollY` from a ref so it's always accurate without causing additional renders.

